60 TRUST~
Syntax: trust <character> <level>

TRUST sets a character's trust to the specified level.  This is similar to
advancing the character for accessing immortal commands, but has no effect
on combat strength, et cetera.  You can give more trust to mortal (or
immortal) characters to give them access to more power without messing up
the character.  You can also restrict a player's trust to less than their
natural level.

A trust of 0 means to use the character's natural level again.
This also can be abused which is why this is a imp only command.
~

51 TYPE_ARMOR~
Designed specifically for the purpose of protecting its wearer from harm,
armor comes in a variety of shapes, forms, and materials.  From padded
leather armors to bulky plate mail, both material strength and mobility play
a part in the defense.  Please be careful when flagging armor.  All
non-metal armors should be flagged NONMETAL.  Weaves and skills will be
offered to enhance armor, so pay attention to proper flagging.  Variables
entered in the v0, v1, v2, v3 slots should always be positive intergers.  
v0 Protection against piercing attacks.
v1 Protection against blunt attacks.
v2 Protection against slashing/ hacking attacks.
v3 Protection against channelling/ exotic attacks.  (Not saving throws)
~

51 TYPE_CLOTHING~
Clothing, unlike armor, is worn for the purpose of asethetic appreciation as
opposed to practical protection.  Because of this and mud consistancy, it is
required that all objects of the sort be typed and flagged correctly. The
main reason for this is, some weaves will work better on Clothing, and some
skills might only work on Armor.  Because of this, the NONMETAL flag, which
should most always be applied to clothing (save in obvious exceptions),
becomes imperative in keeping mud/ skill/ weave balance.  If you must give
Clothing an Armor Class, give it a weakly rated one.  You might notice that
items typed Armor give Variables at the end for holding AC information.  To
give Clothing an armor value, you must use an Addaffect AC to it.  As
previously stated, if you are to give Clothing an AC, keep it weak, the
highest AC given to an object typed Clothing should be -3.

  See also BUILDING, TYPE, AC_VALUES.
~

0 TYPE_CONTAINER~
Containers come in a variety of different types and sizes.  Basically,
any object that can be used to hold others can be flagged type'd Container,
for the ease of game play.  Hence, items type'd Container can either be belt
pouches, sacks, trunks, scabbards, kettles, or even key rings.  It is really
up to the builder and their creativity.  

Now, for an explanation on Container mechanics:
v0 Weight: this is the largest weight allowed inside the container.
v1 Flags: closeable pickproof closed locked puton
v2 Key: insert the vnum for the key to lock/ unlock it.
v4 Capacity: this is the maximum weight the container can hold.
v4 Weight Multiplier: see below.
 
Weight multipliers define how much of the weight is apparent, as bulking
it generally allows one to balance and handle it better.
MIN Weight Multiplier, level -16: 90
MIN Weight Multiplier, level 17+: 80
MIN Weight Multiplier, level 40+: 70
 
See also: BUILDING.
~

51 TYPE_DRINKCONTAINER TYPE_FOUNTAIN~
Items typed 'drinkcontainer' are objects used to transport liquids to
help a player satiate their thirst.  The may be simple waterskins and
canteens, or even mugs, flasks, chalices, barrels, or inverted skulls.  All
'drinkcontainer's are portable, and thus, should have the 'wear take' flag. 

Items typed 'fountain' are stationary drink reservoirs that players can fill
their drinkcontainers from.  They may be wells, streams, barrels, or marsh
waters.  Fountains may not have the 'wear take' flag, but have the benefit
of allowing a -1 in the Liquid Total and Left variables, making them
infinite.  
 
The variables:
v0 Liquid Total: how much liquid the object can hold.
v1 Liquid Left: how much liquid the object currently holds.
v2 Liquid: what drink is contained within, '? liquid' for types.
v3 Poisoned: is the liquid within poisoned?
 
For values, the current MUD standard are mugs at 5 or 10, canteens at 20,
jugs at 40, and barrels at 100+.  Don't forget to have weights reflect this.
 
See also: BUILDING, TYPE_FOOD, TYPE_POTION
~

51 TYPE_FOOD~
Food is any type of object that the player has a chance to ingest. 
Unlike herbs, food does not give any special effects to the player save sate
their hunger.  For experienced players, you know you can't go around hungry
all the time or else you won't regenerate properly.  Common bread types are
rations, fruits, vegetables, stews, or even frogs.  Though with frogs, I
would highly suggest putting the poison flag on them.  
 
The variables:
v0 Food hours: how long until you will need to eat again.  Nourishment.
v1 Full hours: how full the food makes you.  Calories.
v3 Poisoned: is it poisoned?
 
Generally, snacks should last 5 hours, decent meals should last 10, and big
meals should last 15.  If you get confused with the difference between full
and food hours, feel free to keep the variables the same length.
 
See also: TYPE_HERB, TYPE_DRINKCONTAINER, BUILDING
~

51 TYPE_FURNITURE~
Furniture is any type of object that is designed for players to rest,
sleep, stand, or sit on, or in to facilitate healing.  A number of variables
are offered in their creation, explained below.  
v0 The maximum amount of players able to use the object.
v1 The maximum amount of weight the furniture can support.
v2 The flags: sit_, rest_, sleep_, stand_
-             _on, _in,_inside, or is_place
 
The is_place flag allows players to actually hold conversations and emotes
within the furniture, that only others within it can see.  This is used
by the 'tsay' or 'temote' commands.  Mentioning this in the object's
extra desc is allowed, such as obj 9109.
 
  See also BUILDING, HEAL_RATES
~

51 TYPE_HERB TYPE_POTION~
In the Wheel of Time, there are no mystical herbs that are total cure
alls or steroids.  In the creation of Herbs and Potions, please keep their
relative level to a minimum.  Herbs and potions should not have an affect
past level 10.  And the more powerful ones should have a drawback as well as
a benefit.  Think it through, Feverbane might cure disease, but it also
makes you really groggy.  So a minor cure disease and sleep would do the
trick.  Also, because some herbs and potions have a half life, please feel
free to give them the NOSAVE, ROTDEATH, or HADTIMER flags.  These will prove
useful in getting your area approved.  
 
HERBS
v0 - The level at which the effect is cast.
v1, v2, v3 - The effects the herb applies to its eater.
v4 - Null, has no effect on the player.
~

