-1 'AIEL SOCIETIES'~
There are twelve different Aiel warrior societies.  These societies, with
their Aiel names and Common translations, are listed below:

Seia Doon (Black Eyes)
The Seia Doon are an Aiel society made up of warriors who live on the edge
of their emotions.  They are most likely amongst Aiel to show their feelings
very strongly, and can be quick to anger - especially in matters of honor. 
In battle, they fight almost as berserkers, letting their rages carry them
to victory.  

Far Aldazar Din (Brothers of the Eagle)
Far Aldazar Din are much like the hunter they claim kinship to; ever
watchful, they are observant in the extreme.  They may seem to radiate pride
and confidence, with good reason, as they are Aiel, as deadly as any other
of the land.  They often serve as lookouts and guards amongst the Aiel.  

Rahien Sorei (Dawn Runners)
Carrying the ability of Aiel to run long distances in good time almost to
the exreme, Rahien Sorei are the long-rage spears of the Aiel.  They may be
used to carry messages over a long distance, or be sent ahead of other Aiel
forces to hold an enemy to a position.  Determined men, they rarely fail to
reach a goal.  

Sovin Nai (Knife Hands)
Specialists in unarmed combat, Sovin Nai will usually only carry a working
knife, preferring to use their highly-trained bodies as weapons in all but
the most extreme circumstances.  They are always ready for battle, and
constantly practice to hone their mastery of the body further.  They put
great stock in personal control, and may be utter perfectionists.  

Far Dareis Mai (Maidens of the Spear)
The Far Dareis Mai live as their name implies - warriors to the bone, they
forego marriage and children to dance the spears.  Some are called to be
wise ones, or leave their spears for a man, but some remain Maidens until
the end.  They are conscious of their place in Aiel culture, and strive to
be as good as or better than any man in what they do.  They may often seek
out danger or duty, and feel their honor strongly.  Maidens often serve as
scouts, and are almost always on the front line in battle.  

Hama N'dore (Mountain Dancers)


Cor Darei (Night Spears)
The work of the Cor Darei is after the sun has sunk.  At ease in the dark,
they are skilled in performing night-time attacks.  They may slip past most,
if not all of a hold's guard before being discovered.  Tending to be
soft-spoken and subtle, they place the utmost importance on stealth.  

Aethan Dor (Red Shields)
At any large gathering of Aiel, or even in the hold, Aethan Dor serve as
watchmen and guardians.  Often working as a guard system, they will
apprehend any criminals, and generally keep the peace.  Still powerful in
battle, one of thier charges will break any line.  Sometimes imperious, they
are usually generous and helpful, although their wrath is strong.  

Shae'en M'taal (Stone Dogs)
Shae'en M'tall are a proud group, both of their confidence in battle, and
their prowess.  Their charges cannot be held against, and they are usually
the last to leave a battle, functioning as a rear guard during withdrawals. 
Some even go so far as to vow never to retreat from battle.  Their pride
leads them to be touchy about their honor, and they make jests about others
swiftly.  

Sha'mad Conde (Thunder Walkers)
The Sha'mad Conde are fearsome in battle, huge, powerful men of the Aiel.
Although they are considered noisy and slow by their brethren, they are as
swift and deadly as any Aiel.  

Tain Shari (True Bloods)

Duadhe Mahdi'in (Water Seekers)
Masters of finding water almost anywhere, the Duadhe Mahdi'in are usually
the ones who find campsites, and sites for new holds.  Able to survive
virtually anywhere in the Threefold land, they are often solitary men,
sometimes ranging far into the wilderness for periods of time.  
 
Mera'din (the Brotherless)
 Aiel who joined the Shaido - though not of the clan - unwilling to 
aknowledge Rand al'Thor as the Car'a'carn, or unwilling to accept the 
origins of the Aiel.  Denied acceptance in their societies amongst the
Shaido for the act of abandoning sept and clan, they formed their own 
society, the Botherless.
 
See also AIEL, AIEL CLAN
~

-1 'AIEL WAR'~
AIEL WAR (976-978)

When King Laman (LAY-mahn) of Cairhien cut down Avendoraldera,
four clans of the Aiel crossed the Spine of the World. They looted and
burned the capital city of Cairhien as well as many other cities and
towns, and the conflict extended into Andor and Tear.  By the conventional
view, the Aiel were finally defeated at the Battle of the Shining Walls,
before Tar Valon; in fact, Laman was killed in that battle, and having
done what they came to for, the Aiel recrossed the Spine. 
 
  See also ANDOR, CAIRHIEN, SPINE OF THE WORLD.
~

-1 'AIEL WASTE' 'THREE-FOLD LAND'~
AIEL WASTE

Called Djevik K'Shar, "The Dying Ground" in the Trolloc tongue, The
Three-Fold Land (known to outsiders as the Aiel Waste) is a harsh, rugged,
desert land, and home to a harsh, rugged people known as the Aiel.  The Aiel
have established a reputation as the most deadly fighters on the continent
(if not the world).  Tall, strong, and fast, the Aiel are renowned fighters,
and widely feared and mistrusted throughout the rest of the continent.
Veiling their faces before killing, the Aiel refer to fighting as "the Dance
of spears".  They will not touch a sword even on pain of death, and use only
those weapons which have a utilitarian purpose, as well.  Since the Aiel
War, only peddlers, gleemen, and the Tinkers have been allowed to enter the
Waste.

The Aiel are divided into twelve clans, each as large as a small nation.
These clans regularly fight with each other, as nations do, although their
battles are mostly over small oasis.  In turn, these clans are divided into
septs, with no set number of septs for each clan.  In addition, the warrior
class of the Aiel is divided into twelve societies.  These societies span
several clans, and members will not fight other warriors from the same
society, even though they may be of different clans.  For this reason, there
is always communication between clans, even when they are at war with one
another.

One of the Aiel warrior societies is Far Dareis Mai, or the Maidens of the
Spear.  The Maidens of the Spear are female warriors, widely known to be
just as ferocious in battle as their male counterparts.  The Maidens may
bear children, but they may not marry and remain a Maiden.  Upon becoming a
Maiden, the woman is told: "You may belong to no man, nor any man belong to
you, nor any child.  The spear is your lover, your child, and your life."

Despite their reputation for fierce battle, not all Aiel are warriors.
There is a large class of craftsmen, and many Aiel never fight in wars, even
though they are all trained in basic fighting techniques.  In addition,
those women who can channel, and even some who cannot, become Wise Ones.
Those men who are discovered to be able to channel are expected to go into
the Blight to try and kill the Dark One.

Recently, Rand al'Thor has led the Aiel over the Dragonwall and into
Cairhien.  After defeating the rebel Shaido clan, which had laid siege to
the city, those Aiel who followed Rand took control of the city.  They were
also involved in the successful assault Rand, who they call the Car'a'carn
(he who comes with the dawn), against Illian.

See also RHUIDEAN, COLD ROCKS HOLD, WISE ONES, AIEL SOCIETIES, CLANS,
AIEL WAR, CADIN'SOR, GAI'SHAIN, CAIRHIEN.
~

0 'AMYRLIN SEAT'~
The woman called the Amyrlin Seat, informally called the Amyrlin, is the
ruler of all Aes Sedai and the White Tower. All Aes Sedai are pledged
to obey her without question. She is called Mother by Tower folk, and
calls them Son, Daughter, or Child in reply. She is of all Ajahs and none,
although her assistant, the Keeper of the Chronicles, is always raised
from the same Ajah. There have been but two Amyrlins from the Red Ajah
before recent times, and both almost destroyed the Tower entirely.

The Amyrlin is most probably one of the most powerful women in the world.
More powerful than any king or queen, the Amyrlin Seat makes many thrones
tremble. NO ONE refuses a summons to the Amyrlin.

The seal of the Amyrlin is the White Flame. The role of this woman is to
watch over the seals on the Dark One's prison, but few remember that, let
alone realize that the location of the seals has been a mystery since the
Trolloc Wars.

See also: AES SEDAI, AJAH
~

-1 'ARAD DOMAN'  'BANDAR EBAN'~
Arad Doman is located just north of the Almoth Plain, and is flanked by the
Aryth Ocean and the Mountains of Mist.  Domani women are known throughout
the continent for their beautiful copper skin and graceful movement.  Domani
girls are taught the art of seduction from childhood, and only Sea Folk
women can outmatch them for sensuous grace.  As it happens, most Domani
merchants are women.  It is very hard to come out ahead when dealing with a
Domani, but most men consider it worth the experience.

The capital city of Arad Doman is Bandar Eban.  Bandar Eban lies on the
Aryth Ocean and Domani merchants trade often with the Sea Folk, selling
their goods to inland consumers.  In addition, Arad Doman trades often with
Tarabon and Saldaea, although trade with Tarabon is often replaced with war
over the disputed Almoth Plain.

