-1 'TAR VALON'~
Tar Valon is an island city located on the River Erinin, between the
Borderlands to the north and the kingdoms of the south.  The Ogier-built
houses, palaces, and towers which grace the city attract many visitors every
year, of every nationality.  Tar Valon is approximately three to four miles
across, and most of that space is dedicated to parks and gardens.  There are
two harbors in the city, one on the northern tip of the island, the other on
the southern tip.  The White Tower, the center of the power of the Aes
Sedai, dominates the center of the city, and, indeed, a council of Aes Sedai
is responsible for the ruling of the city.  Representatives of every nation
live and work within the walls of Tar Valon, mostly dealing either in trade
or with the Aes Sedai.  Since it was established in 98 AB, the city has
never fallen to invaders, and has seldom been attacked.  This is partially
due to the fact that the island can only be reached by crossing long,
Ogier-built bridges, or by boat, but is mostly because of the hundreds of
Aes Sedai in the White Tower at any one time.

  See also AES SEDAI, GAIDIN, COUNTRIES.

~

1 'THE BLEAKNESS' BLEAKNESS~
The Bleakness is a term given by the Aiel to a sickness caused by learning
that rather than having always been fierce warriors, their ancestors were
strict pacifists forced into defending themselves during the Breaking of the
World and the years following. This knowledge os revealed at Rhuidean, to the
select few who journey there. Many feel that this was their failure of the
Aes Sedai. Some of those effected by the Bleakness throw down their spears
and run away, never to be seen again. Others refuse to put off the gai'shain
white when their time is up. Still others deny the truth of this, and with
it deny necessarily that Rand al'Thor is the Car'a'carn; these either return
to the Aiel Waste or join the Shaido clan opposing him.

See also AIEL, GAI`SHAIN, RHUIDEAN~

0 'THREE OATHS'~
When raised to an Accepted, these Oaths are made when holding the Oath Rod,
which binds them to keep the Oath as firmly as their skin keeps their
insides in.

1. To speak no word that is not true.

2. To make no weapon for one man to kill another.

3. Never to use the One Power as a weapon except against Darkfriends or
Shadowspawn, or in the last extreme of defending her own life, that of her
Warder, or that of another Sister.


The First Oath is often weaseled around by the Aes Sedai. This is probably
why there is a saying: "The truth an Aes Sedai speaks is not always the
truth you think it is". It was not always necessary to swear oaths, when
people knew what the Aes Sedai stood for. But it became necessary to calm
the nations' fear of them using the Power as a weapon against them.

See also: AES SEDAI
~

0 'TIME OF MADNESS'~
Though Lews Therin and his Hundred Companions were successful in
the Sealing of the Bore, their actions unwittingly led to a greater
disaster than anything that had occurred during the War of the Shadow
known also as the War of the Power.  At the moment of the sealing of
the Dark One into his prison, a "backblast" tainted the male half of
the One Power, saidin, even as the Companions were drawing upon
it. It is not certain if this was a desperate action by the Dark One
or simply a consequence of his efforts to prevent the Bore from being
sealed.  This "backblast" led to the greatest calamity the world that has
been recorded, the Breaking of the World.

Lews Therin along with the surviving members of the Hundred
Companions, went instantly insane after the "backblast", and perhaps
never knew that their attempt to seal the Bore had been successful.
These insane male Aes Sedai armed with the One Power, began
unleashing an onslaught with the One Power, against anything and
anyone that crossed their path or even caught their attention.  Trails of
wanton destruction and death, were left behind.

Until that point in time, the One Power had never before been used in such
a violent and insane manner.  The minds of all the surviving Companions
were twisted by the taint into having dreams of madness, and saidin
gave them the power to make these dreams an instant reality. The most
notable of these, was the leader of the Hundred Companions, Lews
Therin (also remembered as the Dragon).  He became remembered as
Lews Therin "Kinslayer" for having not only wreaked vast devastation
upon the land, but also killed every living person who carried any of his
blood, as well as everyone he loved.  The individual acts of destruction
by most of the Companions may have never been recorded, save that they
were known to be on a scale the likes of which had never been known.

Lews Therin and his Hundred Companions were not the only ones
affected by the backlash that was the result of the Sealing of the
Bore.  Other male Aes Sedai who touched on the True Source for
various matters, were also affected by the taint and resulting madness.
These male Aes Sedai, unlike the Companions, were not affected
instantly.  Some time passed before these men began to go insane. Over
time more and more male Aes Sedai were succumbing to the madness,
creating upheaval with the world before their inevitable death, and as
their numbers increased, chaos increased along with them, and civilization
itself deteriorated.

The Breaking of the World, a result of this Time of Madness, put an
end to the War of the Shadow, and is believed to have lasted between
239 to 344 years. Survival, and not war became the focus of both sides.
During the worst of the Time of Madness, mad male Aes Sedai, who could
wield the One Power to a degree now unknown, caused the weather to
protest, resulting in storms of unimaginable fury that shook the world.
Volcanos erupted violently and these male Aes Sedai, in the grips of
their madness, leveled mountains, raised new mountains, and lifted sea
floors resulting in flooding dry land. The earth trembled and seas boiled.

The results were crumbled cities, with their once prosperous inhabitants
scattering to search for safety in the world of madness. Some male Aes
Sedai had sought shelter in Ogier steddings, where the Power did not
work and the True Source could not be sensed.  But by the end of the
Breaking, all the male Aes Sedai that had sheltered in the
stedding had left. Nearly three centuries later, the death of the last
male Aes Sedai marked the end of the Time of Madness and the
Breaking of the World, but most of the land's civilizations were
reduced to the most primitive nomadic levels, even after the climate and
geologic fabric of the earth settled into a normalcy. A few groups,
however, managed to keep some hold on their traditions and culture.
~

